[1] USA (New York)
Date: 28 Jan 2017
Source: Patch [edited]
http://patch.com/new-york/westislip/case-measles-infant-confirmed-suffolk-county


The Suffolk County Department of Health Services (SCDHS) has been notified of a laboratory confirmed case of measles in an infant who arrived recently from overseas.

The child was taken to Good Samaritan Hospital Medical Center emergency room in West Islip on 19 Jan 2017 for evaluation and was released and was then seen at HRHCare Martin Luther King Jr. Family Health Center in Wyandanch on 25 Jan [2017].

To prevent the spread of measles, which is a highly communicable disease, Suffolk health officials are urging anyone who may have been exposed and who has symptoms consistent with measles to call their physicians, health care providers or emergency rooms before going for care.

If it is not possible to call ahead, individuals with symptoms should identify themselves as a potential measles patient immediately upon presentation so that others are not exposed in a waiting room.

[See full article at URL above for exposure sites, dates, times.]

Only people with 2 documented measles-containing vaccines, a blood test showing immunity, or those born (and who lived in the United States) prior to 1957 are considered immune to measles. People who have had only one measles vaccine dose should obtain a 2nd dose.

"We are in close contact with Good Samaritan Hospital, HRHCare, and the New York State Department of Health," Suffolk Commissioner of Health Services James Tomarken said. "Good Samaritan Hospital and HRHCare are reaching out to individuals who were exposed to measles on the dates of potential exposure. However, there may be others who were exposed and whose contact information we do not have. We ask anyone who was at these locations and may have been exposed to be alert for symptoms and to contact their health care providers immediately if they experience symptoms."

Individuals who may be at high-risk for complications from measles include children less than a year old, pregnant women and immunocompromised persons.

Measles symptoms generally appear in 2 stages: early symptoms include a runny nose, cough and a fever. Eyes may become reddened and sensitive to light, while the fever may gradually rise each day. Later symptoms begin on the 3rd day and consist of a temperature of 101 F [38 C] or higher, and a red, blotchy rash lasting 4-7 days. The rash usually begins on the face and then spreads over the entire body. Little white spots may also appear inside the mouth. Symptoms usually appear in 10-12 days after exposure, although they may occur as early as 7 or as late as 21 days after exposure.

Measles is spread by direct contact with nasal or throat secretions of infected people or by airborne transmission. Measles is one of the most contagious communicable diseases and can be contracted at any age.

For facts about measles, visit http://www.health.ny.gov/publications/2170 or http://www.cdc.gov/measles/index.html.

[Byline: Ryan Bonner]

