[4] Pakistan (Sindh)
Date: Tue 31 Jan 2017
Source: The Express Tribune [edited]
http://tribune.com.pk/story/1311802/measles-outbreak-ghotki-claims-one-life/


So far, only one casualty has been reported from Jhando Sanghar village: 4-year-old RS.

The medical superintendent of Taluka Hospital, Ghotki, Dr Lutufullah, told The Express Tribune that the severity of the disease has been reduced during the last week. Earlier, 10 to 12 children were brought to the hospital's outpatient department, out of which we would admit 2-3, he said. "Most people prefer to take their children to private hospitals and clinics instead of government hospitals," he explained.

Dr Pribh Das, who runs a private hospital in Ghotki, said that the measles outbreak has been continuing for the last 2 months. 8-10 children are brought to his hospital every day, and so far only one casualty has been reported. "The severity of the virus is much less than in 2013, when hundreds of children lost their lives," he claimed.

According to him, measles takes 7 days to subside, and it is important to provide proper nutrition to the patient. "It is a common practice in rural Sindh that people stop giving any food and even water to the infected child, due to which their immune system becomes weaker," he explained.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is not clear why disease severity this year [2017] is significantly less than seen in 2013, but that is a good sign. Perhaps case management has improved, or vaccine coverage. Climatic factors also may have contributed to damaged hospitals and clinics in 2013, compromising health care.

Pakistan has a poor health care system, unsanitary conditions in many regions due to poverty, and a lack of education about how to prevent disease. Pakistani officials believe that the worst-hit areas in 2013 were poverty stricken areas where children did not receive vaccination.

Many Pakistanis, especially in rural areas, view vaccination campaigns with suspicion as a western plot to sterilise Muslims. Furthermore, Sindh province, the area hardest hit by the measles outbreak [in 2013], was battered by repeated floods that damaged hospitals and clinics. This may have contributed to the poor recovery observed that year (excerpted from http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/01/20131282648859762.html).

A map of Pakistan can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4808554,140. - Mod.LK]

******
[5] Romania
Date: 29 Jan 2017
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/romania-anti-vaxxer-movement-results-huge-measles-surge-2016/


Romania saw 15 measles cases in 2015. Since 2016, this number has risen up to 2165, including 13 fatalities. This is largely due to bogus claims from anti-vaccination campaigns in the country, according to a La Vanguardia report (computer translated).

President of the Romanian Society of Microbiology Alexandru Rafila directly points the finger at the anti-vaxx movement and says, "Incorrect information, often tendentious, not based on scientific methods or real data, should end so that they do not affect the health of our children."

Mercury in vaccines, vaccines introducing foreign elements, and vaccines causing asthma are some of the arguments made by the anti-vaccination movement. This misinformation has resulted in vaccination rates in the measles-mumps-rubella (MMR) vaccine falling from 95% of children in 2013 to 80% in 2016, and it continues to drop.

Campaigns led by the Christian Orthodox Pro Vita Federation, author of the 2012 book "Vaccines: Prevention or Illness," Christei Todea-Gross, and the Coalition for the Family have spread the anti-vaccination message through a number of outlets.

The Ministry of Health has been denouncing "the irresponsible campaigns against the vaccination of children" for months; however, there are many parents who do not vaccinate their children for lack of confidence towards the authorities.

[Byline: Robert Herriman]

--
